central role that Mackenzie King played in the creation of P.C. 1003. Although most scholars describe the Prime Minister’s approach to policy decisions as calculating and opportunistic, Power, Politics, and Principles argues that Mackenzie King’s adherence to moderate principles resulted in a less hostile legal environment in Canada for workers and their unions in the long run, than a more far-reaching collective bargaining law in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aLabor policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751513340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487515133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487515133.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles